1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:04,886
Even a capable model will fail repeatedly when its tools are difficult to understand.

2
00:00:04,836 --> 00:00:08,214
Humans need a well-designed interface to use software.

3
00:00:08,214 --> 00:00:11,951
Models need a clear agent-computer interface to use tools.

4
00:00:11,951 --> 00:00:21,173
Tool names must be specific, parameters must be unambiguous, and the contract should show input formats, boundaries, examples, and edge cases.

5
00:00:21,173 --> 00:00:23,961
Similar tools need obvious differences.

6
00:00:23,961 --> 00:00:29,230
Errors should state what failed, which input was invalid, and whether a retry is safe.

7
00:00:29,230 --> 00:00:32,355
Do not make the return format harder than the task.

8
00:00:32,355 --> 00:00:38,500
Forcing a model to place large blocks of code inside heavily escaped JSON creates avoidable errors.

9
00:00:38,500 --> 00:00:46,192
Return only the information needed for the next decision; dumping an entire log into context increases cost and hides the useful signal.

10
00:00:46,192 --> 00:00:50,721
Anthropic found that its coding agent often made mistakes with relative paths.

11
00:00:50,721 --> 00:00:55,730
Changing the tool to require absolute paths made those mistakes much harder to produce.

12
00:00:55,730 --> 00:00:58,326
So do not optimize only the prompt.

13
00:00:58,326 --> 00:01:03,048
Observe how the model misuses the interface, then change the interface itself.

14
00:01:03,048 --> 00:01:11,721
Before release, test missing parameters, invalid paths, repeated calls, timeouts, and recovery behavior, not just ideal examples.

15
00:01:11,721 --> 00:01:13,259
Chapter recap.

16
00:01:13,259 --> 00:01:17,519
First, names, parameters, and boundaries must be clear.

17
00:01:17,519 --> 00:01:21,413
Second, return formats should not create extra difficulty.

18
00:01:21,413 --> 00:01:25,442
Third, design the interface so common errors are harder to make.
